<ns0:entry xmlns:ns0="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:ns1="http://schemas.google.com/g/2005" xmlns:ns2="http://schemas.google.com/projecthosting/issues/2009" ns1:etag="W/&quot;C08EQ347eCl7ImA9WhdVFEo.&quot;">
		<ns0:id>http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/2141</ns0:id><ns0:author>
			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">with CL to permit manifest file I/O before the plugin initializes the SRPC and Pepper proxy interfaces, the plugin main thread and the untrusted main thread initially run decoupled / asynchronously.  only when the nexe makes an upcall signalling it is ready to become an event handler will the interfaces get loaded etc and the loadend events fire.

this means that a badly behaved nexe could cause the load to never finish.  this was already possible before, except that the plugin main thread was tied up and the failure mode would be an unresponsive tab; now, the main thread remains free and the tab should be responsive -- the nexe just never finishes loading.

consider adding a time-out mechanism, so that an appropriate error event can fire.  also consider the alternative of leaving the time-out handling to be done in javascript, using ready_state changes, since the plugin main thread is not tied up.

also consider doing the srpc connection and pepper api binding in a background thread.  if this is easily doable, this would enable us to get rid of the synchronization upcall.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-09-19T22:36:42.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-08-09T20:49:47.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>WontFix</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
